Theory:

The Linux mv command is used to move or rename files and directories. Internally, it uses system calls (kernel APIs) like:

rename() → to rename or move files within the same filesystem
link() and unlink() → used when moving across different filesystems
🔹 Key Concept:
Shell commands interact with the kernel through system calls
mv does not copy file contents; it updates file references (in most cases)
If source and destination are on different filesystems, it performs copy + delete

